    &amp;sup2;&amp;sup3;  Originally issued as a home video in 1994, the Peter Tosh                         &amp;sup3;&amp;plusmn;
    &amp;sup2;&amp;sup3;  biography Stepping Razor Red X was finally reissued on DVD   			      &amp;sup3;&amp;plusmn;
    &amp;sup2;&amp;sup3;  in 2002. Tosh narrates the majority of the                                        &amp;sup3;&amp;plusmn;
    &amp;sup2;&amp;sup3;  hour-and-a-half-long documentary himself, utilizing                               &amp;sup3;&amp;plusmn;
    &amp;sup2;&amp;sup3;  cassettes that the famed reggae artist recorded between                           &amp;sup3;&amp;plusmn;
    &amp;sup2;&amp;sup3;  1983 and 1987, in hopes of one day issuing an autobiography                       &amp;sup3;&amp;plusmn;
    &amp;sup2;&amp;sup3;   called Red X (its title came from the fact that whenever                         &amp;sup3;&amp;plusmn;
    &amp;sup2;&amp;sup3;   Tosh saw his name on an official document, a red X   				      &amp;sup3;&amp;plusmn;
    &amp;sup2;&amp;sup3;   was next to it). The tapes were discovered in 1990 and serve  			      &amp;sup3;&amp;plusmn;
    &amp;sup2;&amp;sup3;    as an honest glimpse into the mind of Tosh. All aspects of   				&amp;sup3;&amp;plusmn;
    &amp;sup2;&amp;sup3;   his life are studied, from his poverty-stricken upbringing   				&amp;sup3;&amp;plusmn;
    &amp;sup2;&amp;sup3;   in Jamaica, through his co-founding of the Wailers along   				&amp;sup3;&amp;plusmn;
    &amp;sup2;&amp;sup3;   with Bob Marley and Bunny Wailer, his solo career, and   				&amp;sup3;&amp;plusmn;
    &amp;sup2;&amp;sup3;   eventually, the incidents leading up to his violent and tragic  			&amp;sup3;&amp;plusmn;
    &amp;sup2;&amp;sup3;    death in 1987. In addition to Tosh's narration, Stepping   				&amp;sup3;&amp;plusmn;
    &amp;sup2;&amp;sup3;   Razor Red X contains plenty of live footage, as well as   				&amp;sup3;&amp;plusmn;
    &amp;sup2;&amp;sup3;   interviews with acquaintances, including his mother and   				&amp;sup3;&amp;plusmn;
    &amp;sup2;&amp;sup3;   father, plus a few friends who were with Tosh the night   				&amp;sup3;&amp;plusmn;
    &amp;sup2;&amp;sup3;   he was shot and murdered. Due to the story coming straight   				&amp;sup3;&amp;plusmn;
    &amp;sup2;&amp;sup3;   from the source in many instances, few documentaries are   				&amp;sup3;&amp;plusmn;
    &amp;sup2;&amp;sup3;   as real and unfabricated as Stepping Razor Red X. ~   					&amp;sup3;&amp;plusmn;
